  "prompt": "Why can't radio waves transmit through water?",
  "response": "Radio waves can actually transmit through water, but their effectiveness is highly dependent on the frequency of the waves. Lower frequency radio waves, such as those used in extremely low frequency (ELF) and very low frequency (VLF) bands, can penetrate water to some extent. However, higher frequency radio waves, like those used in AM and FM radio, television, and cellular communications, are significantly attenuated (weakened) when they encounter water.\n\nHere's a more detailed explanation:\n\n1. **Attenuation in Water**: Water is a conductive medium, especially seawater, which contains various ions. When radio waves enter water, they induce electric currents in the conductive medium, which dissipates the energy of the waves as heat. This process is known as attenuation. High-frequency radio waves are more prone to this effect because they have shorter wavelengths and higher energy, which makes them more susceptible to absorption by the water.\n\n2. **Dielectric Properties**: Water has a high dielectric constant, which means it can store a lot of electrical energy. This property causes water to strongly absorb electromagnetic waves, particularly those at higher frequencies.\n\n3. **Depth of Penetration**: Lower frequency radio waves can penetrate deeper into water because they have longer wavelengths and less energy, making them less likely to be absorbed. This is why ELF and VLF frequencies are used for certain underwater communication systems, such as those used by sub marines.\n\n4. **Practical Applications**: For practical underwater communication, sonar (sound waves) is often used instead of radio waves because sound travels much more effectively through water. However, for very specific applications, certain low-frequency radio waves can be used to communicate with submerged objects.\n\nIn summary, while radio waves can transmit through water, their ability to do so is limited by their frequency. Lower frequencies can penetrate water to some extent, but higher frequencies are quickly absorbed and cannot travel far through water. For effective underwater communication, other technologies like sonar are typically employed.",
